    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="129"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d129">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/9614</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador on Special Mission</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_RERDI1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reading</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 353</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 2, 1918</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I have just received a telegram
                    from the Prime Minister asking me to convey to the President the sincere thanks
                    of the War Cabinet for his instant and complete response to the appeal of the
                    British and French Governments.<note n="1" xml:id="d129fn1">See telegram
                        transmitted by the Adjutant General, Mar. 29, <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>,
                            <ref target="#pg_187">p. 187</ref>. Response was also made orally by the
                        President to the British Ambassador.</note> It has come as the greatest
                    relief to all those who have the immediate responsibility for dealing with this
                    crisis to know that, thanks to the President’s prompt co-operation, the Allied
                    armies are to receive an indispensable reinforcement of men during the next few
                    vital months.</p>
                <p>May I ask you to be good enough to convey to the President the above message from
                    Mr. <persName corresp="#p_LGD1">Lloyd George</persName>.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d129fn2">Shown to the President, Apr. 2.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RERDI1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Reading</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
